item.description:
When building high-performance APIs with Spring Boot, we've found that caching can make a huge difference. We can use Redis to cache frequently accessed data. For example, if we're building a REST API that fetches user data from a PostgreSQL database, we can cache the user data in Redis to avoid hitting the database on every request. 

We can use the @Cacheable annotation in Spring Boot to achieve this. Here's an example: 
```java
@Cacheable("users")
public User getUser(String id) {
    return userRepository.findById(id);
}
```
This way, when we call the getUser method, Spring Boot will first check the Redis cache for the user data. If it's not found, it will fetch the data from the PostgreSQL database and cache it in Redis for future requests. This can significantly improve the performance of our API. We don't need to write any extra code to handle the caching logic, Spring Boot takes care of it for us.

We've all been there - our Spring Boot app is running slow and we can't figure out why. One thing that can help is caching. We can use Redis to cache frequently accessed data. Here's a simple example of how to do it:
```java
@Bean
public RedisTemplate<String, String> redisTemplate(RedisConnectionFactory cf) {
    RedisTemplate<String, String> redisTemplate = new RedisTemplate<String, String>();
    redisTemplate.setConnectionFactory(cf);
    return redisTemplate;
}
```
This sets up a Redis template that we can use to cache data. We can then use this template to cache the results of expensive database queries. This can greatly improve our app's performance. Spring Boot also provides a number of other tools to help with performance optimization, including built-in support for caching and profiling tools. By using these tools we can identify performance bottlenecks and fix them.

Most developers default to standard `@Transactional` annotations across their service layer. But if you're fetching data without modifying it, you're wasting memory and CPU cycles.

When you mark a method as `@Transactional(readOnly = true)`, Hibernate turns off dirty checking for managed entities. It skips taking snapshot copies of your domain objects, which lowers memory overhead during high-throughput reads. If you're using PostgreSQL, it also lets your driver optimize database-level transactions and route queries to read replicas.

Here's how it looks:

```java
@Service
public class UserService {

    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public UserResponse getUserDetails(Long id) {
        User user = userRepository.findById(id)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new NotFoundException("User missing"));
        return new UserResponse(user.getId(), user.getName(), user.getEmail());
    }
}
```

Small tweaks like this keep your heap footprint tiny. That's how we run Spring Boot, PostgreSQL and Redis workloads on cheap $1 VPS instances without crashing under peak load.

Most developers blame Hibernate when response times spike. Usually, the real bottleneck is database connection pool starvation. By default, Spring Boot HikariCP allocates connections eagerly, even when your API is just waiting on a slow third-party HTTP call. 

If you don't configure this right, your $2 VPS will crash under minimal load.

To fix this, keep network hops outside your `@Transactional` blocks. Run your external API calls first, then open the transaction, write to the database and close it immediately. 

Also, enforce read-only transactions for fetch queries:

```java
@Transactional(readOnly = true)
public ProductDto getProduct(Long id) {
    return repository.findById(id)
        .map(ProductDto::new)
        .orElseThrow();
}
```

This simple annotation prevents Hibernate from dirty checking, optimizes connection routing and helps your app scale on cheap hardware.

When building high-traffic Spring Boot apps, we've found that database queries can be a major bottleneck. To mitigate this, we can use Redis as a caching layer. We can store frequently accessed data in Redis and reduce the load on our PostgreSQL database. 

For example, we can use the `@Cacheable` annotation in Spring Boot to cache the result of a method. Here's a sample code snippet: 
```java
@Cacheable("users")
public List<User> getUsers() {
    return userRepository.findAll();
}
```
This way, we don't need to query the database every time we need to fetch the list of users. We can't stress enough how much of a performance boost this can give our app. By implementing caching, we can significantly improve our app's response time and reduce the load on our database.
